[[File:Cameo August BM Gem3577.jpg|thumb|The [[Blacas Cameo]] (early 1st century AD), depicting Augustus wearing an [[aegis]]]] The '''Augustalia''', also known as the '''''Ludi Augustales''''' ("Augustan Games"), was a [[Roman festival|festival]] celebrated October 12 in honor of [[Augustus]], the first [[Roman emperor]]. It was established in conjunction with an altar to [[Fortuna Redux]] to mark the return of Augustus from Asia Minor to Rome in 19 BC.{{sfnp|Scheid|2009|page=288}} The [[College of Pontiffs|pontiffs]] and [[Vestals]] conducted [[sacrifice in ancient Roman religion|sacrifices]], and the date became a holiday ''([[Glossary of ancient Roman religion#feria|feriae]])'' on the official religious calendar of Rome.
The altar to Fortuna Redux was [[Glossary of ancient Roman religion#inauguratio|inaugurated]] on October 12, 19 BC, but dedicated on December 15.{{sfnp|Scheid|2009|pages=288–289}} Until Augustus died in 14 AD, Fortuna Redux was the recipient of the day's religious honors, and the name ''Augustalia'' does not appear in sources before that time. During his lifetime, Augustus was honored with ''ludi Augustales'', games ''([[ludi]])'' presented on the initiative of individual [[Executive magistrates of the Roman Empire|magistrates]].{{sfnp|Scheid|2009|page=289}} Strictly speaking, the Augustalia was the anniversary sacrifice, though ''Augustalia'' can also refer to commemorations of Augustus on his birthday, September 23.<ref>Peter Michael Swan, ''The Augustan Succession: An Historical Commentary on Cassius Dio's Roman History Books 55–56 (9 B.C.–A.D. 14)'' (Oxford University Press, 2004), pp. 297–298, 36.<!--more here--></ref>
Augustus lists the establishment of the festival in his posthumously published first-person account of his achievements ''([[Res Gestae Divi Augusti|Res Gestae]])'',<ref>''Res Gestae'' 11.</ref> emphasizing that it takes its name from his ''[[cognomen]]''. Roman festivals were often named for the [[list of Roman deities|deities]] they honored ([[Neptunalia]] for [[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]], [[Cerealia]] for [[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]]), and the unstated implication was that Augustus was to be accorded divine status.{{sfnp|Scheid|2009|pages=288–289}} The establishment of the Augustalia thus marks a major development in what was to become [[Imperial cult (ancient Rome)|Imperial cult]].
The Augustalia, abbreviated as ''AVG'', appears on calendars in large, capital letters like some of the oldest festivals for deities of Rome's archaic religion. It occurs between the [[Meditrinalia]] (October 11) and the [[Fontinalia]] (October 13), both of great antiquity.<ref>Peter Thonemann, "The Tragic King: Demetrios Poliorketes and the City of Athens," in ''Imaginary Kings: Royal Images in the Ancient Near East, Greece and Rome'' (Franz Steiner, 2005), p. 85.</ref>
==See also== * [[Imperial cult (ancient Rome)]] * [[Sodales Augustales]]
